40|$|In this paper, we {{construct}} {{a model of}} market structure in the global arms industry linking concentration, military procurement, international trade and regional conflict. We show how concentration depends on the willingness of producers to import for their military needs and on the relative size of the external market of non-producers. We show {{that there can be}} substantial gains to producers from cooperation in the procurement process, but also small gains to non-producers involved in regional <b>arms</b> <b>races.</b> <b>Arms</b> export controls that limit the level of technology that can be exported to non-producers distribute these cooperative gains from producers to non-producers. military procurement; market structure; <b>arms</b> trade; <b>arms</b> <b>races...</b>|$|R
